1 (c) The operator yields the right-of-way to all oncoming traffic
2 that constitutes an immediate potential hazard;
3 (d) In crossing a divided highway, the crossing is made only at an
4 intersection of such highway with another highway; and
5 (e) Both the headlight and taillight of the vehicle are on when the
6 crossing is made.
7 (6) All-terrain vehicles and utility-type vehicles may be operated
8 outside the corporate limits of any municipality by electric utility
9 personnel within the course of their employment in accordance with the
10 operation requirements of subsection (3) of this section, except that the
11 operation of the vehicle pursuant to this subsection need not be limited
12 to the hours between sunrise and sunset.
13 (7) A city or village may adopt an ordinance authorizing the
14 operation of all-terrain vehicles and utility-type vehicles within the
15 corporate limits of the city or village if the operation is in accordance
16 with subsection (3) of this section. The city or village may place other
17 restrictions on the operation of all-terrain vehicles and utility-type
18 vehicles within its corporate limits.
19 (8) A county board may adopt a resolution authorizing the operation
20 of all-terrain vehicles and utility-type vehicles within any
21 unincorporated village within the county if the operation is in
22 accordance with subsection (3) of this section. The county may place
23 other restrictions on the operation of all-terrain vehicles and utility-
24 type vehicles within the unincorporated village.
25 (9) Except as provided in subsection (10) of this section, the
26 crossing of a controlled-access highway with more than two marked traffic
27 lanes shall be permitted by a utility-type vehicle if the operation is in
28 accordance with the operation requirements of subsection (3) of this
29 section and if the following requirements are met:
30 (a) The crossing is made at an intersection that:
31 (i) Is controlled by a traffic control signal; or
